[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy 1.0 was released on January 2, 2007, and Groovy 2.0 in July, 2012.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Since version 2, Groovy can be compiled statically, offering type inference and performance near that of Java.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy 2.4 was the last major release under Pivotal Software's sponsorship which ended in March 2015.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy has since changed its governance structure to a Project Management Committee in the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] James Strachan first talked about the development of Groovy on his blog in August 2003.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In March 2004, Groovy was submitted to the Java Community Process (JCP) as JSR 241 and accepted by ballot.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Several versions were released between 2004 and 2006.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] After the JCP standardization effort began, the version numbering changed, and a version called "1.0" was released on January 2, 2007.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] After various betas and release candidates numbered 1.1, on December 7, 2007, Groovy 1.1 Final was released and immediately renumbered as Groovy 1.5 to reflect the many changes made.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In 2007, Groovy won the first prize at JAX 2007 innovation award.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In 2008, Grails, a Groovy web framework, won the second prize at JAX 2008 innovation award.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In November 2008, SpringSource acquired the Groovy and Grails company (G2One).
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In August 2009 VMware acquired SpringSource.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In April 2012, after eight years of inactivity, the Spec Lead changed the status of JSR 241 to dormant.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Strachan had left the project silently a year before the Groovy 1.0 release in 2007.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] In Oct 2016, Strachan stated "I still love groovy (jenkins pipelines are so groovy!), java, go, typescript and kotlin".
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] On July 2, 2012, Groovy 2.0 was released, which, among other new features, added static compiling and static type checking.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] When the Pivotal Software joint venture was spun-off by EMC Corporation (EMC) and VMware in April 2013, Groovy and Grails formed part of its product portfolio.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Pivotal ceased sponsoring Groovy and Grails from April 2015.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] That same month, Groovy changed its governance structure from a Codehaus repository to a Project Management Committee (PMC) in the Apache Software Foundation via its incubator.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy graduated from Apache's incubator and became a top-level project in November 2015.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] On February 7, 2020, Groovy 3.0 was released.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Version 4.0 was released on January 25, 2022.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Most valid Java files are also valid Groovy files.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Although the two languages are similar, Groovy code can be more compact, because it does not need all the elements that Java needs.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] This makes it possible for Java programmers to learn Groovy gradually by starting with familiar Java syntax before acquiring more Groovy programming idioms.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy natively supports markup languages such as XML and HTML by using an inline Document Object Model (DOM) syntax.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] This feature enables the definition and manipulation of many types of heterogeneous data assets with a uniform and concise syntax and programming methodology.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Unlike Java, a Groovy source code file can be executed as an (uncompiled) script, if it contains code outside any class definition, if it is a class with a *main* method, or if it is a *Runnable* or *GroovyTestCase*.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] A Groovy script is fully parsed, compiled, and generated before executing (similar to Python and Ruby).
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] This occurs under the hood, and the compiled version is not saved as an artifact of the process.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy offers simple, consistent syntax for handling *lists* and *maps*, reminiscent of Java's *array* syntax.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy offers support for prototype extension through `ExpandoMetaClass`, Extension Modules (only in Groovy 2), Objective-C-like Categories and `DelegatingMetaClass`.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy's changes in code through prototyping are not visible in Java, since each attribute/method invocation in Groovy goes through the metaclass registry.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] The changed code can only be accessed from Java by going to the metaclass registry.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy also allows overriding methods as `getProperty()`, `propertyMissing()` among others, enabling the developer to intercept calls to an object and specify an action for them, in a simplified aspect-oriented way.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] The Grails framework uses metaprogramming extensively to enable GORM dynamic finders, like `User.findByName('Josh')` and others.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy's syntax permits omitting parentheses and dots in some situations.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] enabling the development of domain-specific languages (DSLs) that look like plain English.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Although Groovy is mostly an object-oriented language, it also offers functional programming features.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] According to Groovy's documentation: "Closures in Groovy work similar to a 'method pointer', enabling code to be written and run in a later point in time".
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy's closures support free variables, i.e. variables that have not been explicitly passed as a parameter to it, but exist in its declaration context, partial application (that it terms 'currying'), delegation, implicit, typed and untyped parameters.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Usually called *partial application*, this Groovy feature allows closures' parameters to be set to a default parameter in any of their arguments, creating a new closure with the bound value.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Supplying one argument to the `curry()` method will fix argument one.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Supplying N arguments will fix arguments 1 ..
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Curry can also be used in the reverse direction (fixing the last N arguments) using `rcurry()`.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Groovy also supports lazy evaluation, reduce/fold, infinite structures and immutability, among others.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] On JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) and XML processing, Groovy employs the Builder pattern, making the production of the data structure less verbose.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] and also can be processed in a streaming way through `StreamingMarkupBuilder`.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] To change the implementation to JSON, the `MarkupBuilder` can be swapped to `JsonBuilder`.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] GStrings containing variables and expressions must be declared using double quotes.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] A complex expression must be enclosed in curly brackets.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] According to Groovy's own documentation, "When the Groovy compiler compiles Groovy scripts and classes, at some point in the process, the source code will end up being represented in memory in the form of a Concrete Syntax Tree, then transformed into an Abstract Syntax Tree.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] The purpose of AST Transformations is to let developers hook into the compilation process to be able to modify the AST before it is turned into bytecode that will be run by the JVM.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] The testing framework Spock uses AST transformations to allow the programmer to write tests in a syntax not supported by Groovy, but the relevant code is then manipulated in the AST to valid code.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Traits can be seen as interfaces carrying both default implementations and state.
[src:groovy-lang/apache-groovy] Traits allow a wide range of abilities, from simple composition to testing.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A **Java virtual machine** (**JVM**) is a virtual machine that enables a computer to run Java programs as well as programs written in other languages, other languages referred to as JVM languages that are also compiled to Java bytecode.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM is detailed by a specification that formally describes what is required in a JVM implementation.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Having a specification ensures interoperability of Java programs across different implementations so that program authors using the Java Development Kit (JDK) need not worry about idiosyncrasies of the underlying hardware platform.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM reference implementation is developed by the OpenJDK project as open source code and includes a JIT compiler called HotSpot.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The commercially supported Java releases available from Oracle are based on the OpenJDK runtime.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Eclipse OpenJ9 is another open source JVM for OpenJDK.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine is an abstract (virtual) computer defined by a specification.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] It is a part of the Java Runtime Environment.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The garbage collection algorithm used and any internal optimization of the Java virtual machine instructions (their translation into machine code) are not specified.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The main reason for this omission is to not unnecessarily constrain implementers.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Any Java application can be run only inside some concrete implementation of the abstract specification of the Java virtual machine.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Starting with Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0, changes to the JVM specification have been developed under the Java Community Process as JSR 924.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] As of 2006, changes to the specification to support changes proposed to the class file format (JSR 202) are being done as a maintenance release of JSR 924.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The most commonly used Java virtual machine is Oracle's HotSpot.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Oracle owns the Java trademark and may allow its use to certify implementation suites as fully compatible with Oracle's specification.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Java's design philosophy revolves around the assumption of a garbage collector.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Unlike languages such as C++ and Rust, deterministic memory management through a `delete` keyword (as in C++) is not possible.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Even introducing such a feature is not possible, due to a lack of ownership, aside from using sun.misc.Unsafe or through java.lang.foreign to allocate/deallocate memory outside the Java heap.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Due to Java primarily using heap-based allocation, objects are stored as references, and deletion would result in dangling pointers.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM operates on specific types of data as specified in Java Virtual Machine specifications.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The data types can be divided into primitive types (integer and floating-point values) and reference types.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] `long` and `double` types, which are 64-bits, are supported natively, but consume two units of storage in a frame's local variables or operand stack, since each unit is 32 bits.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`, `byte`, `short`, and `char` types are all sign-extended (except `char` which is zero-extended) and operated on as 32-bit integers, the same as `int` types.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The smaller types only have a few type-specific instructions for loading, storing, and type conversion.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] `boolean` is operated on as 8-bit `byte` values, with 0 representing `false` and 1 representing `true`.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] (Although `boolean` has been treated as a type since *The Java Virtual Machine Specification, Second Edition* clarified this issue, in compiled and executed code there is little difference between a `boolean` and a `byte` except for name mangling in method signatures and the type of Boolean arrays.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] `boolean`s in method signatures are mangled as `Z` while `byte`s are mangled as `B`.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Boolean arrays carry the type `boolean[]` but use 8 bits per element, and the JVM has no built-in capability to pack booleans into a bit array, so except for the type they perform and behave the same as `byte` arrays.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM has a garbage-collected heap for storing objects and arrays.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Code, constants, and other class data are stored in the "method area".
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The method area is logically part of the heap, but implementations may treat the method area separately from the heap, and for example might not garbage collect it.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Each JVM thread also has its own call stack (called a "Java Virtual Machine stack" for clarity), which stores frames.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A new frame is created each time a method is called, and the frame is destroyed when that method exits.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Each frame provides an "operand stack" and an array of "local variables".
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The operand stack is used for operands to run computations and for receiving the return value of a called method, while local variables serve the same purpose as registers and are also used to pass method arguments.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Thus, the JVM is both a stack machine and a register machine.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] In practice, HotSpot eliminates every stack besides the native thread/call stack even when running in Interpreted mode, as its Templating Interpreter technically functions as a compiler.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM uses references and stack/array indexes to address data; it does not use byte addressing like most physical machines do, so it does not neatly fit the usual categorization of 32-bit or 64-bit machines.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] In one sense, it could be classified as a 32-bit machine, since this is the size of the largest value it natively stores: a 32-bit integer or floating-point value or a 32-bit reference.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Because a reference is 32 bits, each program is limited to at most 232 unique references and therefore at most 232 objects.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] However, each object can be more than one byte large, and potentially *very* large; the largest possible object is an array of `long` of length 231 - 1 which would consume 16 GiB of memory, and there could potentially be 232 of these if there were enough memory available.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This results in upper bounds that are more comparable to a typical 64-bit byte-addressable machine.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A JVM implementation can be designed to run on a processor that natively uses any bit width as long as it correctly implements the integer (8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit) and floating-point (32- and 64-bit) math that the JVM requires.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Depending on the method used to implement references (native pointers, compressed pointers, or an indirection table), this can limit the number of objects to less than the theoretical maximum.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A JVM language is any language with functions that can be expressed in a valid class file, which can be hosted by a JVM.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A class file contains JVM instructions (JVM bytecode), a symbol table, and other ancillary information.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The class file format is the hardware- and operating system-independent binary format used to represent compiled classes and interfaces.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] There are several JVM languages, both older established languages ported to JVM, and much newer from-scratch languages.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] JRuby and Jython may be the best known ports of older languages, i.e., Ruby and Python respectively.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Of the new from-scratch languages created to compile to Java bytecode, Clojure, Groovy, Scala and Kotlin may be the most popular.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A notable feature of the JVM languages is their language interoperability, they are compatible with each other, so that, for example, Scala libraries can be used with Java programs and vice versa.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Java 7 JVM implements *JSR 292: Supporting Dynamically Typed Languages* on the Java Platform, a new feature which supports dynamically typed languages in the JVM.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This feature is developed within the Da Vinci Machine project whose mission is to extend the JVM so that it supports languages other than Java.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] One of the organizational units of JVM byte code is a class.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A class loader implementation must be able to recognize and load anything that conforms to the Java class file format.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Any implementation is free to recognize other binary forms besides *class* files, but it must recognize *class* files.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Initialization: invokes Java code that initializes class variables to their proper starting values.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] In general, there are three types of class loader: bootstrap class loader, extension class loader and System / Application class loader.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Every Java virtual machine implementation must have a bootstrap class loader that is capable of loading trusted classes, as well as an extension class loader or application class loader.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The Java virtual machine specification does not specify how a class loader should locate classes.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Each particular host operating system needs its own implementation of the JVM and runtime.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] These JVMs interpret the bytecode semantically the same way, but the actual implementation may be different.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] More complex than just emulating bytecode is compatibly and efficiently implementing the Java core API that must be mapped to each host operating system.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] These instructions operate on a set of common abstracted data types rather the native data types of any specific instruction set architecture.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, common programmer errors that often led to data corruption or unpredictable behavior such as accessing off the end of an array or using an uninitialized pointer are not allowed to occur.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Several features of Java combine to provide this safety, including the class model, the garbage-collected heap, and the verifier.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JVM verifies all bytecode before it is executed.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The first two of these checks take place primarily during the verification step that occurs when a class is loaded and made eligible for use.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The third is primarily performed dynamically, when data items or methods of a class are first accessed by another class.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The verifier permits only some bytecode sequences in valid programs, e.g. a jump (branch) instruction can only target an instruction within the same method.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Furthermore, the verifier ensures that any given instruction operates on a fixed stack location, allowing the JIT compiler to transform stack accesses into fixed register accesses.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Because of this, that the JVM is a stack architecture does not imply a speed penalty for emulation on register-based architectures when using a JIT compiler.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] In the face of the code-verified JVM architecture, it makes no difference to a JIT compiler whether it gets named imaginary registers or imaginary stack positions that must be allocated to the target architecture's registers.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] In fact, code verification makes the JVM different from a classic stack architecture, of which efficient emulation with a JIT compiler is more complicated and typically carried out by a slower interpreter.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Additionally, the Interpreter used by the default JVM is a special type known as a Template Interpreter, which translates bytecode directly to native, register based machine language rather than emulate a stack like a typical interpreter.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Another instance of a stack architecture being merely a specification and implemented in a register based virtual machine is the Common Language Runtime.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The original specification for the bytecode verifier used natural language that was incomplete or incorrect in some respects.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A number of attempts have been made to specify the JVM as a formal system.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] By doing this, the security of current JVM implementations can more thoroughly be analyzed, and potential security exploits prevented.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] It will also be possible to optimize the JVM by skipping unnecessary safety checks, if the application being run is proven to be safe.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A virtual machine architecture allows very fine-grained control over the actions that code within the machine is permitted to take.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] It assumes the code is "semantically" correct, that is, it successfully passed the (formal) bytecode verifier process, materialized by a tool, possibly off-board the virtual machine.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This is designed to allow safe execution of untrusted code from remote sources, a model used by Java applets, and other secure code downloads.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Once bytecode-verified, the downloaded code runs in a restricted "sandbox", which is designed to protect the user from misbehaving or malicious code.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] As an addition to the bytecode verification process, publishers can purchase a certificate with which to digitally sign applets as safe, giving them permission to ask the user to break out of the sandbox and access the local file system, clipboard, execute external pieces of software, or network.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] For each hardware architecture a different Java bytecode interpreter is needed.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] When a computer has a Java bytecode interpreter, it can run any Java bytecode program, and the same program can be run on any computer that has such an interpreter.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] When Java bytecode is executed by an interpreter, the execution will always be slower than the execution of the same program compiled into native machine language.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This problem is mitigated by just-in-time (JIT) compilers for executing Java bytecode.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A JIT compiler may translate Java bytecode into native machine language while executing the program.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The translated parts of the program can then be executed much more quickly than they could be interpreted.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This technique gets applied to those parts of a program frequently executed.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] This way a JIT compiler can significantly speed up the overall execution time.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] There is no necessary connection between the Java programming language and Java bytecode.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A program written in Java can be compiled directly into the machine language of a real computer and programs written in other languages than Java can be compiled into Java bytecode.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Java bytecode is intended to be platform-independent and secure.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Some JVM implementations do not include an interpreter, but consist only of a just-in-time compiler.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Java 22 introduces the Foreign Function and Memory API, which can be seen as the successor to Java Native Interface.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Native methods are enable by JNI to handle situations when an application cannot be written entirely in the Java programming language, e.g. when the standard Java class library does not support the platform-specific features or program library.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The JNI framework lets a native method use Java objects in the same way that Java code uses these objects.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A native method can create Java objects and then inspect and use these objects to perform its tasks.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A native method can also inspect and use objects created by Java application code.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] JNI also allows direct access to assembly code, without even going through a C bridge.[3] Accessing Java applications from assembly is possible in the same way.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] At the start of the Java platform's lifetime, the JVM was marketed as a web technology for creating Rich Web Applications.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] As of 2018, most web browsers and operating systems bundling web browsers do not ship with a Java plug-in, nor do they permit side-loading any non-Flash plug-in.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The Java browser plugin was deprecated in JDK 9.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The NPAPI Java browser plug-in was designed to allow the JVM to execute so-called Java applets embedded into HTML pages.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] For browsers with the plug-in installed, the applet is allowed to draw into a rectangular region on the page assigned to it.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Because the plug-in includes a JVM, Java applets are not restricted to the Java programming language; any language targeting the JVM may run in the plug-in.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] A restricted set of APIs allow applets access to the user's microphone or 3D acceleration, although applets are not able to modify the page outside its rectangular region.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Adobe Flash Player, the main competing technology, works in the same way in this respect.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] As of June 2015 according to W3Techs, Java applet and Silverlight use had fallen to 0.1% each for all web sites, while Flash had fallen to 10.8%.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Since May 2016, JavaPoly allows users to import unmodified Java libraries, and invoke them directly from JavaScript.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] JavaPoly allows websites to use unmodified Java libraries, even if the user does not have Java installed on their computer.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] With the continuing improvements in JavaScript execution speed, combined with the increased use of mobile devices whose web browsers do not implement support for plugins, there are efforts to target those users through transpilation to JavaScript.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] It is possible to either transpile the source code or JVM bytecode to JavaScript.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Compiling the JVM bytecode, which is universal across JVM languages, allows building upon the language's existing compiler to bytecode.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] The main JVM bytecode to JavaScript transpilers are TeaVM, the compiler contained in Dragome Web SDK, Bck2Brwsr, and j2js-compiler.
[src:groovy-lang/java-virtual-machine] Leading transpilers from JVM languages to JavaScript include the Java-to-JavaScript transpiler contained in Google Web Toolkit, J2CL, Clojurescript (Clojure), GrooScript (Apache Groovy), Scala.js (Scala) and others.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:groovy-lang/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
